96 to 1200":"from 1196 to 1200","Galloway,Scotland":"Kirkcudbrightshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland.":"Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Falde,Dumfriesshire, Scotland.":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Armstrong","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (mainly Northumberland and the Scottish Borders): nickname from Middle English <i>arm</i> + <i>strang</i>, for someone who was ‘strong in the arm’.","Irish (Ulster): adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Labhradha Tréan</b> ‘strong O'Lavery’ or <b>Mac Thréinfhir</b>, literally ‘son of the strong man’.","History: This surname was brought to PA, NJ, and NH in the 18th century by several different families of northern Irish and northern English Protestants. One such was James Armstrong, who emigrated from Fermanagh to Cumberland County, PA, in 1745; another was John Armstrong (1720–95), who settled in Carlisle, PA, <i>c.</i> 1748."],"variants":[{"name":"Armstong","meanings":["Altered form of English   Armstrong  ."]}]},{"name":"Alan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alan John Armstrong was born in 1164, in Kirkcudbrightshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, David Armstrong, was 17 and his mother, Mrs. David Armstrong, was 17. He married Margaret De Mormaer from 1196 to 1200, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1255, in Scotland, at the age of 91."},"et":{"1164–1255":"1164–1255","1173–1228":"1173–1228","1196–1271":"1196–1271","–Male":"Surnud","1147–1200":"1147–1200","1228":"1228","1147":"1147","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","1164":"1164","1196":"1196","1173":"1173","1271":"1271","1196 to 1200":"1196 kuni 1200","Galloway,Scotland":"Kirkcudbrightshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland.":"Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Falde,Dumfriesshire, Scotland.":"Dumfriesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1164–1255":"1164–1255","1173–1228":"1173–1228","1196–1271":"1196–1271","–Male":"Kuollut","1147–1200":"1147–1200","1228":"1228","1147":"1147","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","1164":"1164","1196":"1196","1173":"1173","1271":"1271","1196 to 1200":"vuodesta 1196 vuoteen 1200","Galloway,Scotland":"Kirkcudbrightshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland.":"Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Falde,Dumfriesshire, Scotland.":"Dumfriesshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1164–1255":"1164–1255","1173–1228":"1173–1228","1196–1271":"1196–1271","–Male":"Décédé","1147–1200":"1147–1200","1228":"1228","1147":"1147","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","1164":"1164","1196":"1196","1173":"1173","1271":"1271","1196 to 1200":"du 1196 au 1200","Galloway,Scotland":"Kirkcudbrightshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Scotland.":"Écosse","Scotland":"Écosse","Falde,Dumfriesshire, Scotland.":"Dumfriesshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Alan John Armstrong est né en 1164, à Kirkcudbrightshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni, son père, David Armstrong, avait 17 ans et sa mère, Mrs. David Armstrong, avait 17 ans. Il a épousé Margaret De Mormaer du 1196 au 1200, à Écosse. Ils ont e